s not so forgiving; In fact, Grant thought he would ensnare Lee by April 5. This, of course, did not happen. See for example, Davis, To Appomattox, 173. at his house, Clover Hill: At Clover Hill, over iced tea, Judge Cox\x{2019}s daughter Kate quipped to Lee: \x{201c}General, we will still win. You will join General Johnston in North Carolina, and together you will win!\x{201d} Lee replied: \x{201c}Know this, whatever happens, no men fought better than mine,\x{201d} Davis, To Appomattox, 166\x{2013}70; Trudeau, Campaign to Appomattox, 9. But now, a mere administrative mix-up: To this day, it is not clear just what happened and how; it remains one of the great historical mysteries of this war; Trudeau does say that \x{201c}Lee himself doomed this plan when, on April 4, he decided to stop at Amelia \x{2026} to reprovision his army. The stop accomplished none of Lees intended objectives,\x{201d} \x{201c}A Mere Question of Time\x{2019}\x{201d} 549; of course, it would have been different had there been food; Trudeau further counters that there was \x{201c}something irrational about the whole enterprise \x{2026} Lee made no effective attempt to provide rations in anticipation of the move,\x{201d} 548\x{2013}49. For his part, Calkins says that the heart of the Confederate cause had stopped beating long before its military and political leaders acknowledged the fact, Final Bivouac, 201, 208. I would put it differently. The heart was there, but in light of the, Amelia disaster, the food wasn\x{2019}t\x{2014}and now the Confederate limbs began inexorably to fail, fate and luck \x{2026} smoke of a skirmish: Indeed, on the morning of April 9, Phil Sheridan, on the way to meet with Gordon, narrowly missed getting killed by a Confederate sharpshooter\x{2019}s bullet, Stern, End to Valor, 253.",
