            "When the Founders first debated to who would be the Unions next president (entire section on succession): For the best treatment of this too little studied but crucial subject, see Silva, Presidential Succession, which has the most precise statement of what the Framers intended, and Stephen W. Stathis\x{2019}s excellent \x{201c}John Tyler\x{2019}s Presidential Succession: A Reappraisal,\x{201d} in Prologue 8, no. 4 (1976): 223\x{2013}36. Also Stephen Wilhelm, \x{201c}The Origins of the Office of the Vice Presidency,\x{201d} Presidential Studies Quarterly 7, no. 4 (1977): 206\x{2013}14. This section draws extensively upon these three fine works, from which all quotes are taken, unless otherwise noted, and which have influenced my thinking and argumentation heavily. I am much indebted to these studies. Other very useful studies that I have used are: Michael DiSalle, Second Choice (Hawthorne, 1966); Merrill Jensen, The Making of the American Constitution (Van Nostrand, 1964); Jonathan Elliot, ed., The Debates on the Adoption of the Federal Constitution, vols. 1\x{2013}5 (William S. Hein, 1888); and Edward S. Corwin, The President: Office and Powers 1767\x{2013}1957 (New York University Press, 1991). When the Founders to until that election took place: For this section, see esp. Silva, Presidential Succession, <<1\x{2013}13|5a:1>>, and Wilhelm, \x{201c}Origins of the Office of the Vice Presidency,\x{201d} 36\x{2013}51; also Michael Dorman, The Second Man: The Changing Role of the Vice Presidency (Delacorte, 1968), 45\x{2013}46. they did not intend for the vice president to become president: Wilhelm agrees with this. He also notes that the delegates at the convention did not consider the matter \x{201c}a major topic.\x{201d} And further, that historical documents still \x{201c}leave the question of why the office was even created a mystery,\x{201d} \x{201c}Origins of the Office of the Vice Presidency,\x{201d} 214; Jefferson ally William Rives referred to the whole matter of succession as a \x{201c}remote and shadowy inheritance,\x{201d} Silva, Presidential Succession, 114\x{2013}15. Edward S. Corwin: See Corwin, President, esp. 54. For similar commentaries to Corwin, see also Donald B. Chidsey, And Tyler Too (Nelson, 1978), 44\x{2013}46; Herbert Horwill, The Usages of the American Constitution (Oxford University Press, 1969), 268\x{2013}69; Wilfred Binkley, The Man in the White House (Johns Hopkins University Press, 1968), 268\x{2013}69; Richard H. Hansen, The Year We Had No President (Lincoln, 1962), <<13\x{2013}20|5a:1>>; James Kent, Commentaries on American Law, 4 vols. (W. Kent, 1854), vol. 1, 298; Charles Warren, The Making of the Constitution (Little, Brown, 1937), note at <<637|9c:0>>; and Charles K. Burdick, The Law of the American Constitution: Its Origin and Development (F. B. Rothman, 1922), 59\x{2013}60; for earlier opinions, see John W. Burgess, Political Science and Comparative Constitutional Law (Ginn 8c Company, 1891), 239; William Rawle, A View of the Constitution of the United States (H. C. Carey & I. Lea, 1825), vol. 1, 711; David Watson, The Constitution of the United States: Its History, Application, and Construction, 2 vols. (University of Chicago Press, 1910), vol. 1, 891\x{2013}902. Indeed, for the better part of a half century: On March 1, 1792, Congress did pass a presidential succession law, which provided that a vice president can resign or refuse election in one way only, with a written refusal signed and dated and delivered to the secretary of state, Wilhelm, \x{201c}Origins of the Office of the Vice Presidency,\x{201d} 213. The law also provided that the president pro tempore of the Senate or speaker of the house would be in line to act as president, until presidential electors were chosen or elected and a special election held. One may ask, why was the secretary of state not put in line? The reason was politics, having to do with Alexander Hamilton\x{2019}s hatred of Thomas Jefferson. On this point, the choleric Fisher Ames, Federalist leader in Massachusetts, gleefully reported to Thomas Dwight: \x{201c}The Secretary of State is struck out of the bill for the future presidency, in case of the first two offices becoming vacant. His friends think it important to hold him up as King of the Romans. The firmness of the Senate kept him out,\x{201d} See Silva, Presidential Succession, 113\x{2013}14; for a larger discussion of congressional actions on this matter, occurring in 1792, 1820\x{2013}21, and 1842, see Silva, Presidential Succession, 112\x{2013}16, 166\x{2013}68. Interestingly, when President Johnson was later impeached, many in Congress asserted that he was still \x{201c}vice president,\x{201d} and for the time, only \x{201c}acting president.\x{201d} Others noted simply that he was serving out \x{201c}Lincoln\x{2019}s term.\x{201d} Indeed, the three original impeachment resolutions introduced by Benjamin F. Loan and John Kelso spoke of \x{201c}the officer now exercising the function pertaining to the office of President of the United States\x{201d}; James Ashley\x{2019}s resolution referred to \x{201c}Andrew Johnson, Vice President and acting President of the United States\x{201d}; and another resolution put it this way: \x{201c}Vice President of the United States, discharging the powers and duties of the office of the President.\x{201d} The Final Judiciary Committee resolutions that impeached him, however, did so as the \x{201c}president.\x{201d} See Silva, Presidential Succession, note on 26 and 27. But even the Founders were not omniscient to So by the time Lincoln lay dying: Silva, Presidential Succession, <<14\x{2013}31|5a:1>>, and conclusions, esp. 166\x{2013}69; Stathis, \x{201c}John Tyler\x{2019}s Presidential Succession\x{201d}; also Chidsey, And Tyler Too, esp. 41\x{2013}53; and Dorm\x{e1}n, Second Man, esp. 45\x{2013}55. hours away in Williamsburg: Some 230 miles and at least twenty-one hours, to be exact. This in itself was a telling fact about the lack of importance of the vice presidency. Washington was alive with fierce speculation: Chidsey writes that the capital was in a \x{201c}state of pitiful bewilderment\x{201d} over the succession issue. \x{201c}Learned statesman everywhere were asking themselves the question\x{201d} of succession, which had been left \x{201c}in the air.\x{201d} the cabinet would run the show: As Chidsey puts it: \x{201c}That this amiable Virginian might become \x{2026} the full time, undisputed president, Webster did not for a moment believe\x{201d}; moreover, the secretaries assembled \x{201c}were to rule the nation in Tyler\x{2019}s name,\x{201d} And Tyler Too, 44\x{2013}45. Before relatively newer scholarship, Tyler\x{2019}s succession had been blandly portrayed by some as almost devoid of political intrigue. See Oliver Chitwood, John Tyler: Champion of the Old South (D. Appleton, 1939), 202\x{2013}6; Leonard Dinnerstein, \x{201c}The Accession of John Tyler to the Presidency,\x{201d} Virginia Magazine of History and Biography 70 (October 1952): 447\x{2013}58; Robert Seager, And Tyler Too (Easton Press, 1963). Tyler had won the showdown: Claude Fuess says that Tyler \x{201c}made it entirely clear that he intended to seize full authority,\x{201d} Claude M. Fuess, Daniel Wehster, 2 vols. (Little, Brown, 1930), vol. I, 95. Similarly, of the ambitious Tyler, Morgan argues, \x{201c}Tyler\x{2019}s whole course of action after he arrived in the capital demonstrated [his] serious deliberation to establish himself as President in his own right and not as a mere caretaker for the departed Harrison,\x{201d} Robert J. Morgan, A Whig Embattled: The Presidency Under John Tyler (Lincoln, 1954), 9. special presidential election should be called for: Chidsey points out, however, \x{201c}Could a man in truth be President who had never been elected President? This was the question that perplexed even the most expert hairsplitters in Washington,\x{201d} And Tyler Too, 50. administered not by Chief Justice Taney: One unsatisfactory reason could be that Taney was a resident of Baltimore, while Cranch lived in Washington. But this still does not explain his essential refusal to administer the oath to Tyler. See Bernard Steiner, Life of Brooke Taney: Chief Justice of the United States Supreme Court (Williams &Wilkins, 1922), 257\x{2013}58.",
