hodox philosophy of war, and reiterated his maxim of getting there first. He also said he preferred \x{201c}pistols to sidearms.\x{201d} In this same meeting, he spoke openly, without recrimination, of the rebel effort in Mississippi to enroll Negroes in the army, suggesting he was a convert to this view, see, for example, Hurst, Nathan Bedford Forrest, 246\x{2013}47. Fort Pillow: The truth of the killing of several dozen black prisoners and some whites\x{2014}including Major William Bradford, the commander, who was captured and subsequently killed, is now generally accepted. For more on Fort Pillow, see Ronald K. Hugh, \x{201c}Fort Pillow Massacre: Aftermath of Paducah,\x{201d} Illinois State Historical Society Journal 66 (1973): 62\x{2013}70, and George Bodnia, ed., \x{201c}Fort Pillow \x{2018}Massacre,\x{2019} Observations of a Minnesotan,\x{201d} Minnesota History 4 (1973): 186\x{2013}90; Albert Castel, \x{201c}The Fort Pillow Massacre: A Fresh Examination of the Evidence,\x{201d} CWH 4, no. 1 (March 1958): 48; and John Cimprich and Robert Mainfort Jr., \x{201c}Fort Pillow Revisited: New Evidence About an Old Controversy\x{201d} CWH 28 (1982): 293\x{2013}306. It could be added that General Bill Sherman, who faced accusations of brutality as well, after examining the evidence, was satisfied that Forrest had done what he could to halt excesses, and that the slaughter of \x{201c}negro troops\x{201d} was not, \x{201c}properly speaking, a \x{2018}massacre\x{2019} so much as the rather unnecessary killing of blacks due to their panic,\x{201d} see Lewis, Sherman, 370. Qualifying a wholesale acceptance of Sherman\x{2019}s assessments are his own questionable racial biases and the accusations he had to face, significant morale booster for the South: See Gallagher, Confederate War, 36\x{2013}37. \x{201c}blood can not restore blood\x{201d}: See BC, 794. \x{201c}niggers\x{201d} and \x{201c}Tories\x{201d} alike, had it corning: See Albert Castel\x{2019}s introduction on this